  "content": " guarantee the product safety. The supplier shall have a documented process for the management of “product safety” related products and manufacturing processes. Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA) requires their suppliers to designate a Product  Safety Representative (PSCR (Product Safety & Conformity Representative)) to be in charge of all related tasks described in IATF 16949 section 4.4.1.2. Furthermore, the supplier shall apply these requirements to their supply chain. Suppliers of safety critical components will be required to participate in Safety Management Audits. 3.6 Cybersecurity Supplier  must be able to demonstrate an Information Security Program which is formal, supported and maintained. This includes, but is not limited to: • Information Security policies and controls • Security Incident Response and Communication Plan • Security Awareness Program which includes simulations and user training • Identification and Management of security risks Evidence of compliance may include an Information Security Certification (e.g., ISO27001, TISAX, SOC (Substances of Concern) 1 or 2) from an external auditing body or a security assessment initiated by Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA) which may be performed onsite or remote. EA-QM-xx-M-740, Rev New, 11/12/2024 Supplier  agrees to respond to requests about policies and timely report any cybersecurity breaches that could impact Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA). 4. New Parts/Products For each new part / product or first time buy for Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA), the supplier must submit initial samples (IS (Initial Sample)) with a complete report, handling manuals and other supporting documents in accordance with requirements of IATF 16949, related AIAG (Automotive Industry Action Group) / VDA (Verband der Automobilindustrie (German Automotive Association)) manuals APQP (Advanced Product  Quality Planning) & PPAP (latest edition) and any other OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer)/Customer specific requirements specified during contract release free of charge. The report must contain Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA) part number, technical engineering level and clear and complete supplier identification data. PPAP (Production Part Approval Process) packages must be complete, accurate and up to date for the products / parts in question always. Samples shall be provided free of charge to PTC (Porto Technical Centre) Testing Centre for SoC (Substances of Concern) testing, to the relevant Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA) manufacturing plant for assembly trials, and to the SQE (Supplier  Quality Engineer) upon request (see 4.6). The suppliers of proprietary or other products /parts must provide documented evidence of formal OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) / customer approval of product validation, which clearly demonstrates conformance to Yazaki (Yazaki EMEA) requirements and OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer)/customer requirements, including a signed PSW (Part Submission Warrant). Where PSW (Part Submission Warrant)’s must be updated on a regular basis, according to OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) requirements e.g. annual lay-outs, suppliers will be notified by SDDC (Supplier  Development Documentation Center) to submit updated PPAP (Production Part Approval Process) documentation free of charge. Initial"
